<br>
My shaman often used to fire off his slows by /assisting the puller when he heard an &quot;INCOMING&quot; message, before he ever saw the mob, and the slow would land right when the mob popped into view.  Or not land, either way.  Sometimes he could debuff the mob with malo on the way in, then start casting slow.<br>
<br>
Now, he's going to have to wait until he sees the mob, which very often in dungeons is when it's already right in the camp.  He may have to cast two slow-casting spells(malo and slow) before the mob is even slowed, or, if he has only one fail, three spells starting from pretty much when the mob is already in camp.  That's a fair amount of time spent.<br>
<br>
Offensive spells in general supposedly have to be cast when you can see the mob, too.  That will cut back on a fair bit of spell firing, too.  My shaman and druid both used to DOT, and my shaman would JBB blast, mobs he couldn't see at first.  Now, if a mob flees, he has to leave the camp and chase it to land a blast or a DOT if it turns a corner.<br>
<br>
This actually makes things quite a bit harder in some situations.<br>
